 Co., Peter Bent Brigham Hospital, and others","start_year":null,"end_year":null}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"legacy","header":"He bought his ancestor’s house to save it","body":"In 1902 Reynolds, a great-great-grandson of Paul Revere, purchased the decaying Revere house in the North End and formed an association to restore it as a museum. It survives as the oldest building in downtown Boston."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"He kept the letters of the abolitionists","body":"As grandnephew of Wendell Phillips, Reynolds preserved Phillips’s collection of letters from the leading abolitionists, Susan B. Anthony, Garrison, Emerson, Lydia Maria Child, and others. The correspondence is now catalogued at the Harvard Library."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"He carried Revere money to a Union spy","body":"In the 1880s and ’90s Reynolds traveled to Richmond to deliver money from the Revere family to the aging Union spy Elizabeth Van Lew, who had cared for two imprisoned Revere cousins. After her death he marked her grave with a boulder from the Massachusetts State House."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"He raced a Kaiser and built a galleon","body":"A passionate yachtsman, Reynolds raced the German Kaiser at Kiel and the young King of Spain at Bilbao in 1907, then published his account anonymously as \"The Cruise of the Golden Eagle.\" His Maine vacation house, designed to resemble a Spanish galleon, still stands as a coastal landmark."},{"number":5,"category":"business","header":"He moved a museum and shunned the credit","body":"Among the financiers who relocated the Museum of Fine Arts to Huntington Avenue and built the Copley Plaza on its old site, Reynolds preferred to organize ventures without taking visible charge. He disliked being photographed, and pictures of him are scarce."}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I01833","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1884,"children_ids":["HD6585","HD6586"]}],"cross_connections":[{"ty